To all of our kiddos and families, have the best summer ever! Thank you for being so awesome!

Monday, 3/23: Kids’ Webinar! Marine Mammals in Your Backyard

For the past 6 years, scientists from NOAA Northeast Fisheries Science Center and the Woods Hole Sea Grant have joined TCS students and staff for NOAA Ocean Day at TCS. This upcoming week would have been year 7! But don’t worry. As luck would have it, Grace Simpkins, who always brings INCREDIBLE activities and lessons to Ocean Day is holding a 45 minute webinar on Monday, March 23 at 11am EST. post_text: TCS students and staff were Holiday Helpers this week. We supported the Truro Police and Fire Departments and Lower Cape Ambulance in their annual food and toy drive at Savory. Then we walked as a school to Savory to deliver our donations. ♥️🧣

post_text: Today, the 6th graders finally finished the huge job of counting and rolling all of the change collected in their Sneakers to Make Smiles service learning project. They were able to purchase 24 pairs of new sneakers for Mass Appeal’s spring sneaker drive for young children on the Lower Cape. The students will also be donating $135.32 to the organization to purchase additional new pairs of sneakers. A total of $500.00 was raised from our TCS students and community donating coins during a three week period. Well done TCS and thank you 6th graders!

post_text: Happy Earth Day! 🌏 Today students in grades K-6 welcomed scientists from NOAA Northeast Fisheries Science Center and the Woods Hole Sea Grant to TCS for our 6th Annual Ocean Day. We learned about marine mammals, bioacoustics, animal adaptations and climate change, marine food webs, Atlantic salmon, sea turtles, and fishing gear and bi-catch. Thank you to our scientists for a great day of learning! 🌊

post_text:
Way to go Ranger Chris Anderson for helping care for this nearly 300 pound loggerhead that was rescued on Great Island in Wellfleet. Chris is one of our very own TCS family members!
>>>>>>> master

TCS students learn how to care for and report cold-stunned sea turtles. If you find a cold-stunned sea turtle, carefully move it above the tide line, picking it up on the sides/underneath its shell. Note that the turtle may appear deceased. Follow all these steps anyway. Cover it with dry seaweed if possible. Mark the location with driftwood, marine debris, or a pile of sand. Note the location and call Audubon in Wellfleet. (508) 349-2615 x-6104. Put this # in your phone contacts, just in case.
shared_text:
Mass Audubon Wellfleet Bay Wildlife Sanctuary
November 21, 2018 at 7:54 PM ·

Wow--more than 300 cold-stunned sea turtles so far this fall and today-- a nearly 300 pound loggerhead was rescued from Great Island in Wellfleet. Thanks to our volunteers Bruce Hurter and Charlie Sullivan for finding it and to Chris Anderson, CCNS ranger, for helping us to get this possibly record-sized turtle for Massachusetts off the beach and to the New England Aquarium for medical care. Whew...

Calling all 4th graders! Did you know there’s a special pass that allows you free entrance to national parks, including national seashore beaches? The Every Kid in a Park program encourages 4th graders and their families to explore our wonderful federal lands. Students who completed 4th grade during the 2017-18 school year may obtain a voucher at www.everykidinapark.gov. Passes expire 8/31/18. Rising 4th graders may obtain the 2018-19 pass during the upcoming school year. We learned about personal watercraft safety, boating safety, and the Coast Guard. Now we know how to be “Semper Paratus”—always prepared. Thank you so much for visiting! Families, remember, if you have kayaks, canoes, or SUPs and would like an identification sticker, we have a limited number available in the office. You can also send a note in with your student and we’ll send it home.

We have a limited number of identification stickers for personal watercraft (kayaks, canoes, SUPs) available in the Main Office. They were provided by the USCG Auxiliary Nauset Flotilla 11-6. These ID stickers can help rescuers know whether or not a drifting watercraft was accidentally launched or if there is a potential need for rescue by providing owner identification. If you take a sticker, we ask that you follow through and attach it to your watercraft.

The Flotilla held a safety course on the Lower Cape recently. Although the course has passed, this article has great tips on water craft safety for the summer.

post_text: Boo the diamond backed terrapin is headed back to the wild today to begin his adventures! He’s been wintering over in the first grade classroom, having been hatched at Audubon too late in the season. Ms. Picariello went through special training on how to care for Boo. It’s been fun to track his growth and observe his behaviors. Good luck, little one! We’ll all be routing for you!

post_text:
In an effort to keep all our kids safe, this is from our friends at the Truro Police Department:

Truro Central School Community,

Massachusetts State law requires all drivers to stop when a school bus has its flashing lights on and its stop sign out. This includes student drop off and pick up times on school grounds.

Recently, motorists have been observed driving past the school buses in the Truro Ceutral school parking lot, while the buses warning lights have been activated, and children are entering or exiting the buses.

The State Department of Health and Human Services reports that the majority of injuries to do with school buses are children hit by passing cars, with children between ages 4 to 7 at greatest risk.

In response, Officers of the Truro Police Department, in collaboration with the Truro Central School, will be present at the school during drop off and pick up times for the purpose of enhancing safety.

For more information on School Bus Safety, visit www.mass.gov

In partnership with the community,

Craig L. Danziger
Chief of Police
Truro Police Department

Truro Public Library
>>>>>>> master
March 2, 2018 at 4:40 PM ·

For the month of March, art created by the students of The Truro Central School, under the instruction of art teacher Kim Possee, will be on exhibit in the Anne Brock Community Room.

This year's installation features architectural paintings, landscapes, weavings and figurative sculptures. Pictured is a local sunset landscape by Jada and a portion of a sculpture of a business woman by Carolina. Come take a look at this inspiring work by our youngsters!

March 2, 2018 at 4:40 PM ·

For the month of March, art created by the students of The Truro Central School, under the instruction of art teacher Kim Possee, will be on exhibit in the Anne Brock Community Room.

This year's installation features architectural paintings, landscapes, weavings and figurative sculptures. Pictured is a local sunset landscape by Jada and a portion of a sculpture of a business woman by Carolina. Come take a look at this inspiring work by our youngsters!

post_text:
One of our recently retired teachers, Mrs. Gazzano, shared this exciting event with us!

“I've been walking the beach each fall for 10+ years looking for cold stunned turtles with my second grade class and Audubon, but in all those walks never found one. So this morning, in my first year of retirement, while walking on Corn Hill Beach guess what I find?! To make this even better, as this turtle was placed near the parking lot to be picked up by Audubon, who should come down the boardwalk but Ms. Rose, Ms. King and Ms.Fitzgerald and this year's 2nd grade on the hunt for stranded turtles! How great is that!”

That’s a great story!

If you find a sea turtle on the beach...
-Move the turtle above…

Our annual Thanksgiving Feast is a time for students and teachers to share a meal together, cooked with love by Susie and Jamie. Families donate their time and goodies for dessert. Our town seniors also “come to school” for lunch. As one of our guests commented, “Our bellies are full and we are happy!”

Have a wonderful Thanksgiving, everyone! There is much to be thankful for here in Truro!

Some students and teachers participated in the parade as well.

post_text: Another great Chronicle on WCVB Channel 5 airing tomorrow night (Tuesday, 7/25) at 7:30pm!!! This one features the Cape Cod Maritime Museum and we hope to see cameos of some of our TCS graduates who built the first of our Bevin's Skiffs. He is wearing the white hat in the photo of the museum's replica of the catboat SARAH. ⛵️⚓️

post_text: 4th graders recently finished reading the book "Because of Winn-Dixie" by Kate DiCamillo. One of the most memorable scenes is Opal's party at Gloria Dump's house. Teachers recreated the party as a surprise for the 4th graders complete with streamers and pictures of dogs for decorations, a jar of pickles, egg salad sandwiches cut into little triangles, Litmus Lozenges (aka root beer and strawberry hard candies) and Dump Punch (grapefruit and orange juices). They were so surprised and happy! ❤️

text: https://facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=309112172866441&id=229106630866996
video_thumbnail: 4th graders recently finished reading the book "Because of Winn-Dixie" by Kate DiCamillo. One of the most memorable scenes is Opal's party at Gloria Dump's house. Teachers recreated the party as a surprise for the 4th graders complete with streamers and pictures of dogs for decorations, a jar of pickles, egg salad sandwiches cut into little triangles, Litmus Lozenges (aka root beer and strawberry hard candies) and Dump Punch (grapefruit and orange juices). They were so surprised and happy! ❤️

post_text: A great article about our NOAA Ocean Day!
shared_text:
NEFSC.NOAA.GOV
Students Pledge to be “Ocean Minded” at Truro’s NOAA Ocean Day

NOAA Fisheries New England/Mid-Atlantic
April 7, 2017 at 8:43 AM ·

Students at Truro Central School in Cape Cod pledged to be open-minded about being ocean minded. Our NOEPS team spent time with Truro Central’s students talking about marine mammals, food webs, sea turtles, fishing, by-catch, endangered Atlantic salmon, bioacoustics, adaptations, and climate change. Learn more about NOAA’s Ocean Day at Truro Central School by visiting http://bit.ly/2nlcWFa

Are you or someone you know an educator interested in sharing hands-on activities about these topics with students? Visit the NOEPS website for lesson plans and resources: http://bit.ly/2nNCrf0

post_text: Looking for something to do during vacation week? How about a road trip to Woods Hole for some science-inspired fun? While you're there, stop by the NOAA Woods Hole Science Aquarium at the end of Water Street. There are seal feedings at 11 and 4. WHOI also has a great little museum on School Street that features a full sized model of the inner sphere of the submersible ALVIN.
